<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Burma </F>
<H3> <TI>   Singapore's Prime Minister Goh Visits </TI></H3>
<H4>   Promotes Constructive Dialogues </H4>
<F P=102> BK3003132094 Singapore Singapore Broadcasting Corporation in 
English 1100 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK3003132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Singapore Singapore Broadcasting Corporation </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong says the policy of 
isolating Myanmar [Burma] has not worked. He said the 
international community should instead engage in constructive 
dialogues with Yangon [Rangoon] if it wants to seek change in 
the country. Speaking at the end of his three-day official 
visit to Myanmar, Mr. Goh said that after many years of 
self-isolation, the country now wants to open up its economy. 
He said ASEAN's policy of constructive engagement is the right 
one. The prime minister also encouraged businessmen and leaders 
from Western countries to visit Myanmar to assess the situation. 
More importantly, such visits will give them the opportunity to 
put forward their viewpoints to the country's leadership. 
  Myanmar's minister for national planning and economic 
development, Brigadier General David Abel, said Mr. Goh's visit 
has built a lot of confidence in the business community. He 
added he now expects better rapport between businessmen in the 
two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

