<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajina-Croatian Cease-Fire Extended to 31 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602161794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1458 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2602161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Knin, 26 Feb (TANJUG) -- The republic of Serb 
Krajina and the Republic of Croatia today signed a document 
extending the cease-fire agreement until 31 March. Apart from 
the extension of the cease-fire, the warring sides agreed to 
continue talks on reaching a general cease-fire. 
  This is the third time the cease-fire agreement between 
Krajina and Croatia -- originally signed on 17 December 1993 -- 
has been extended. The cease-fire has been holding, apart from 
sporadic provocations on the part of the Croatian Army, 
especially in northern Dalmatia and Lika. 
  In the presence of Colonel Wood and UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Forces] Commander Jean Cot the [extension] document was signed 
by Colonel Kosta Novakovic, assistant commander of the Serb 
Krajina army, in agreement with the civilian and military 
authorities of Krajina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

