<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Mediation in Ties With Athens Rumored </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2702172094 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2702172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nevenka Jovicic] </F>
  [Text] Judging by everything, it appears that Moscow is 
taking the initiative in resolving the strained relations 
between Athens and Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM], which will, if it proves as successful as 
in the recent Russian action that stopped NATO bombing in 
Bosnia, confirm the authority and power of the new Russian 
foreign policy. 
  The announcement of Russian mediation in a dispute in the 
south of Balkans will not please the West and NATO in the least. 
They are, according to what the weekly TO VIMA TIS KIRIAKIS 
writes today, already rather alarmed by Russia's rapid and 
unexpected diplomatic offensive. 
  Although Greece's official reply to Moscow's proposal to 
mediate in resolving the dispute with Skopje has not been made 
public here, TO VIMA announces the beginning of a new action by 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev, who is already supposed 
to visit FYROM next week. 
  This latest move by Moscow in an area of the Balkans in 
which 
Washington and NATO have shown such an open interest will cause 
new worries for the West, political circles here assess. It is 
also being pointed out that the worries of the West will be even 
greater as this latest Russian diplomatic action confirms the 
increasingly closer links between Russia and Greece, which are 
drawn together by friendship between peoples, the same religion, 
and historic roots. 
  The West's fears of Russia's growing role have already 
resulted in the so-called Partnership for Peace agreement 
starting to take the shape of an association of countries based 
on exclusively anti-Russian orientation, TO VIMA comments. 
  Greece itself announces a much more active and aggressive 
policy in the Balkans to protect its national interest. 
According to Khristos Saliberis, chief of the Greek General 
Staff, carried by today's TO VIMA, Greek policy is moving from 
the defensive to the offensive, which basically means the 
neutralization of aggressive neighbors like Turkey and 
protection of Greeks from Epirus to Cyprus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7728 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu039_m_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-039 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister, Opposition Leader View Blockade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802094494 Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network in German 
0600 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2802094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Veronika Seyr from Skopje] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] The Greek punitive blockade 
is not only causing serious economic damage in Macedonia [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM], a country that 
has been strangled by Yugoslavia's disintegration, the wars in 
Croatia and Bosnia, and the UN embargo against Serbia. The 
economic situation is desperate and the political consequences 
are unpredictable, says Petrus Stefanov, economics minister in 
Skopje. 
  [Begin Stefanov recording, in Macedonian with superimposed 
translation into German] The blockade is seriously endangering 
our economy, but it also affects the overall political 
situation. It is a direct attack on the stability of the whole 
region. [end recording] 
  The nationalist opposition in Macedonia sees all its fears 
confirmed. Ljupco Georgijevksi from the Internal Macedonian 
Revolutionary Organization says: 
  [Begin Georgijevski recording, in Macedonian with 
superimposed translation into German] The decision of the Greek 
Government has not surprised me very much. It is the logical 
consequence of the Greek policies of the past three years. I 
would not be surprised either if Athens were to resort to 
military means. This is a cold war against Macedonia, a cold 
war which is aggravating the conflicts in the whole of the 
Balkans and also has consequences for Europe. Accordingly, we 
deplore that the European Community is not doing enough. [end 
recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

