<H3> <TI>   General Staff: No Aircraft Overflying Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802113294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1007 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belgrade, 28 February (TANJUG) -- The General 
Staff of the Yugoslav Army categorically rejects the possibility 
that the four planes that were shot down this morning by NATO 
fighters belonged to the Yugoslav Air Force, a TANJUG journalist 
was told today by the Yugoslav Army General Staff. 
  Yugoslav Army planes, respecting the UN Security Council 
resolution banning flights over the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
did not fly around or overfly this zone, the Yugoslav Army 
General Staff stresses. 
  Since the establishment of the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia, Yugoslav Army planes have not flown outside FRY air 
space, they stress at the General Staff. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

