<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic Warns on Croat-Muslim Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702204794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1855 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2702204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belgrade, Feb 27 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Foreign 
Minister Vladislav Jovanovic expressed fear on Sunday that no 
peaceful motives stood behind the pressures on the Bosnian 
Moslems and Croats to renew their alliance. In a statement to 
the Kragujevac radio, Jovanovic warned that a strategy of 
forming an alliance between the two Bosnian peoples against the 
third (Bosnian Serbs) would lead to further escalation of the 
crisis and the continuation of war. 
  The Yugoslav foreign minister lent support to any effort 
towards narrowing differences between any of two peoples in the 
former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, except those 
motived by the formation of alliance against a third people. 
  Jovanovic said he was confident that on the Croat side those 
forces interested in peace are stronger than those which would 
like to seek their chance in some new war adventure. 
  At the initiative of Washington, the talks between Croatia, 
the Bosnian Croats and Moslems on a common Bosnian Croat-Moslem 
state opened on Saturday. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

