<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rugova on Clinton Policy, Mazowiecki Report </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2502191094 Tirana Radio Tirana Network in Albanian 1430 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2502191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana Radio Tirana Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Albanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Dr. Ibrahim Rugova, president of the 
republic of Kosova, gave a news conference in Prishtina today. 
Let us go to a report by Leke Musolli: 
  [Musolli] In today's news conference Ibrahim Rugova, 
president of the republic of Kosova, first welcomed the attitude 
of U.S. President Bill Clinton for not leaving the question of 
Kosova out of the ultimatum addressed to Serbs. With this, it 
is seen that Kosova and the Albanian question will take their 
rightful place in the final solution to the crisis in former 
Yugoslavia. 
  Rugova then briefed reporters on the present reality in 
Kosova, characterized as it is by Serbian police violence and 
terror. Recently, the Serbian courts convicted dozens of 
Albanians to more than 100 years of imprisonment on trumped-up 
charges. President Rugova said that this violence by the 
Serbian police aims to imprison Albanians and compromise their 
peaceful policy for resolving the question of Kosova. 
  Rugova illustrated the intensity of the police violence with 
the closure of the Academy of Sciences and Arts of the republic 
of Kosova. However, in spite of this, the Academy of Sciences 
and Arts of the Republic of Kosova will continue to exist and 
will continue to work and cooperate with all the foreign 
academies, as it has been doing for many years. This shameful 
act and the recent police repression have increased the tension 
in Kosova. That is why president Rugova invited the public and 
international diplomats to take steps to prevent any possible 
conflict in Kosova. 
  Speaking about the recent initiatives on solutions to the 
problems in former Yugoslavia, Dr. Rugova concentrated on that 
of Russian President Boris Yeltsin. Rugova said that we would 
not like this to replace the initiative for a global solution of 
the problems in former Yugoslavia and that we do not want 
another Yalta in the Balkans. Mr. Rugova said that we would not 
like the role of the Russian factor in this region to be 
one-sided. President Rugova said that the Balkans should not be 
considered as a region of spheres of interest. On the contrary, 
it should be seen as a sphere of integrating processes. 
  At today's news conference, President Rugova welcomed the 
visit of Albanian President Dr. Sali Berisha to Brussels and 
added that signing the Partnership for Peace agreement will be 
important not only for Albanians but for the whole region. He 
also greeted the report by the special envoy of the UN secretary 
general, Mr. Tadeusz Mazowiecki, which objectively described the 
violation of human rights and freedoms in Kosova. 
  At the news conference, Mr. Rugova answered many reporters' 
questions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

