<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Says Prime Minister Often `Ambiguous' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502171794 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Slovak Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik gave a 
news conference late this morning, probably his last as foreign 
minister. Journalists' questions concentrated mostly on the link 
between the internal political situation in Slovakia and 
Slovakia's international standing. [passage omitted] 
  [Begin Moravcik recording] Foreign countries have been 
monitoring the situation in our country very carefully. They 
have drawn one conclusion from our internal situation: that 
there is a trend here to implement certain elements of an 
authoritarian regime. This is one negative factor. 
  The second factor is the fact that statements by some 
politicians--above all, by the prime minister--are frequently 
ambiguous. This makes our internal politics rather 
incomprehensible, and this, of course, influences the 
conclusions drawn by foreign countries as regards their attitude 
toward our country. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

