<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Returns From China, Briefs Media </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502162394 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar has described the 
mutual granting of most-favored-nation status as the greatest 
success of his official visit to the People's Republic of China. 
He said this at a news conference at Bratislava airport, 
immediately after the return of the Slovak delegation. The 
prifme minister considers Thailand to be an important trade and 
economic partner, too. According to Meciar, Slovakia has 
achieved a certain opening with regard to relations with Turkey, 
and Pakistani officials are also showing an interest in visiting 
Slovakia. 
  At the news conference, the prime minister refused to 
comment 
on the resignations of Deputy Prime Minister Roman Kovac and 
Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik. He said that so far he has not 
heard President's Kovac's stand and that he has not yet gathered 
enough information about the matter. He also failed to comment 
on the alleged statements by Jan Slota, the newly elected 
chairman of the Slovak National Party [SNS], who is said to have 
expressed admiration of Russian ultranationalist Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy. The prime minister stressed that the SNS 
continues to be the coalition partner of the HZDS [Movement for 
a Democratic Slovakia]. 
  A trend toward implementing elements of an authoritarian 
regime is what is emerging when the internal political situation 
in Slovakia is assessed abroad. This was said by Foreign 
Minister Jozef Moravcik at a news conference in Bratislava. He 
said that, if this proves to be true, Slovakia's position 
abroad, with regard to its integration into Europe, would 
suffer. Jozef Moravcik expressed the view that Slovakia's 
foreign policy orientation will be preserved because Slovakia 
has already taken important international legal steps in that 
direction, such as signing the association agreement with the 
European Union and the umbrella agreement on participating in 
the Partnership for Peace program. 

</TEXT>

