<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roman Kovac News Conference After Resigning </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502140294 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502140294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Our colleague Bernard Hornak is on the line from an 
extraordinary news conference given by Deputy Prime Minister 
Roman Kovac, who has resigned from his post. 
  [Hornak] At the opening of his news conference, Roman Kovac 
confirmed that at 0900 today he handed his resignation letter to 
President Michal Kovac. He repeated the reasons for his 
resignation. The main reason he gave was that he did not wish 
to be the cause of increased tension in our society. Neither 
did he want to see yet another wave of confrontation between the 
Cabinet and the president. 
  Answering a question as to what in his view is the future of 
the Alternative of Political Realism, Roman Kovac said that the 
Alternative was formed within the HZDS [Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia]. It has proposed a certain solution to the 
political crisis and has called for a return to democratic 
principles. At present, those deputies who have subscribed to 
the ideas of the Alternative are not changing their view. 
  Speaking about his future political line, Roman Kovac said 
that Slovakia needs a consensus and that, at present, on the 
basis of that consensus, he has held talks with the 
representatives of the National-Democratic Club [of the Slovak 
National Party], the Alliance of Democrats, and some 
nonparliamentary parties. 
  This is all for the time being from the presidium of the 
government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

