<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Confirms Aircraft Downed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802085894 Paris AFP in English 0854 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2802085894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Feb 28 (AFP) -- Four Serbian Galeb 
aircraft were shot down by U.S. fighters near the northwestern 
town of town of Banja Luka early Monday [28 February], a NATO 
military spokesman confirmed here. 
  Earlier Admiral Chistos Liberis, the chief of staff of the 
Greek armed forces, announced in Athens that the four Serbian 
aircraft were downed 55 miles (90 kilometers) west of Banja Luka 
between 0430 GMT and 0500 GMT. 
  The NATO spokesman said the Serbian aircraft had ignored 
orders to land relayed to them by NATO aircraft enforcing a 
no-flight ban over Bosnia-Herzegovina as part of operation Deny 
Flight. 
  In Athens, Admiral Liberis made the announcement to 
journalists who were awaiting the end of talks between Defense 
Minister Gerassimos Arsenis and visiting British Foreign 
Secretary Douglas Hurd. 
  In Sarajevo, UN sources said a Serbian aircraft was shot 
down 
by NATO aircraft over the central town of Zenica early Monday 
morning. The Serbian plane had taken off from Banja Luka, they 
added. 
  A spokesman for the United Nations High Commissioner for 
Refugees said the humanitarian airlift into Sarajevo and all 
movements to Serb-controlled areas were being suspended. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

