<F P=103> LD2702185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following the announcement of the arrival in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina of a new contingent of Russian troops, Alija 
Izetbegovic, president of the Bosnia-Herzegovina, today sent a 
letter to Yasushi Akashi, the UN secretary general's special 
envoy. The letter reads: 
  Esteemed Mr. Akashi, the behavior of Russian soldiers on 
their arrival in Sarajevo caused dissatisfaction among the 
citizens, and -- I believe -- damaged the reputation of the UN 
mission in Bosnia-Herzegovina. On their arrival they 
demonstrated support for the aggressor and behaved in a way 
which reminded us of some earlier ugly periods. Our people took 
all this as a provocation which could have turned into an 
incident. 
  Bearing this in mind, it is my duty to inform you that we do 
not agree to the arrival of more Russian troops in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. We believe that decisions to this effect 
should be postponed. We ask you to inform the competent UN 
officials about our position on this issue, Alija Izetbegovic 
says in his letter. 

