<H3> <TI>   Srpska General on Cease-Fire, UNPROFOR </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602214194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1931 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602214194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Novi Sad, Feb 26 (TANJUG) -- Commander of the 
Bosnian Serb Army General Staff, Gen. Ratko Mladic, has said one 
should not worry over the Serb defence positions around Sarajevo 
after the withdrawal of heavy weapons, because the U.N. 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR) was really making an effort to 
maintain ceasefire. 
  If, however, the Moslems launch an offensive (in the 
Sarajevo 
area) the (Bosnian) Serbs will fiercely respond with all 
available means, Gen. Mladic warned in an interview to the Novi 
Sad daily DNEVNIK on Saturday. 
  I would not recommend to Moslems to take up arms. It is 
better (for them) to try to achieve their goals peacefully -- 
through negotiations, in which they can achieve much, because 
they can lose everything by opting for war, he said. 
  In connection with the insistence by some western countries, 
especially france to threaten the Bosnian Serbs with air strikes 
unless they allow the opening of the airfield in Tuzla, Gen. 
Mladic said he was confident that the airfield in that Moslem 
enclave would be least used for humanitarian aid supply. 
  We have reliable information that weapons and ammunition, as 
well as Mujaheddin from Islamic countries would be brought in by 
planes, he said. 
  Stressing that the Serb side will discuss with UNPROFOR the 
possibilities for the opening of the airfield, and that it is 
ready to negotiate this directly with the Moslems, Gen. Mladic 
warned that it should, nevertheless, be clear to everybody that 
Bosnian Serbs would not allow the case of the Sarajevo airport 
to be repeated. 
  "We held the Sarajevo airport, and then turned it over to 
UNPROFOR, and the Moslems dug a tunnel under the airport and use 
it unhindered (for military purposes), despite our warnings to 
the peace-keeping command and U.N. Secretary-General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali," said Gen. Mladic. 
  In connection with the talks on forming a common Bosnian 
Moslem- Croat state, Gen. Mladic said it was possible that a 
Moslem-Croat coalition backed primarily by Croatia, as well as 
many other countries, again take up arms and come against the 
Serbs. 
  As long as the international factors do not want peace in 
Bosnia- Herzegovina, there will be no peace, Gen. Mladic 
concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

