<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Expert on Bosnian Antiaircraft Systems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502190994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1934 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502190994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 17 (TANJUG) -- Paul Beaver, a 
prominent British military expert said Thursday that Bosnian 
Serbs possessed a series of anti-aircraft systems to respond to 
NATO air strikes in case they are launched against the Serbs' 
positions around Sarajevo. 
  The analyst of the British Jane's defence military magazine 
in an interview to the VOA monitored in Belgrade, said that the 
Bosnian Serbs not only possessed missiles with a 40-km range and 
a number of anti-aircraft and shoulder rocket launchers, but 
also a completely new Russian system called SA-16. NATO says 
the system is difficult to counter. 
  Beaver said Bosnian Serbs possessed a large number of 
anti-aircraft cannon and added that most of the aircraft in the 
Gulf war as well as in the Falklands war 12 years ago, were 
known to be shot down by the infantry fire from the ground. 
  The analyst thus warned that the West should not be led into 
believing that the war planes would be able to launch attacks on 
the Sarajevo surroundings without being exposed to danger. 
  He said that on top of that NATO did not have the best 
trained pilots in the world. Last Wednesday NATO threatened the 
Bosnian Serbs and Moslems they would be bombed unless they 
withdrew their heavy artillery in and around Sarajevo or place 
it under U.N. control. 
  Although the NATO ultimatum concerns all three sides to the 
Bosnian conflict, many Western politicians and media regard the 
ultimatum as directed to the Bosnian Serbs alone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

