<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Reports Shelling of Mostar Breaks Truce </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2702134494 Paris AFP in English 1144 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2702134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Medjugorje, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Feb 27 (AFP) -- 
Shelling on the Moslem-held part of Mostar, in southern Bosnia, 
has broken a truce agreed between Bosnian army and Croat 
officials for two days running, a UN spokesman said here Sunday. 
  Eleven shells fell on the eastern part of the city late 
Saturday and two explosions were heard early Sunday in the same 
area, Colonel Antonio Castro of the UN Protection Force's 
(UNPROFOR) Spanish battalion said. 
  "It's the first time the ceasefire has really been 
violated," 
the spokesman said. The truce went into effect on Friday [25 
February] at 1200 GMT. 
  Castro said an investigation would have to be held to 
determine who is responsible for the shelling. The Spanish 
battalion has its headquarters in Medjugorje, around 20 
kilometres (12 miles) from Mostar. 
  The city is divided between the Croat troops who hold the 
western part and have besieged for the past six month the 
Moslem-held eastern part where some 50,000 people are trapped. 
  During the two weeks preceeding the ceasefire agreement, an 
average of the 10 shells fell daily on the eastern part. 

</TEXT>

