<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim Attacks, Muslim-Croat Fighting Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602155394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1524 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2602155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Zvornik, February 26 (TANJUG) -- Fighting continued 
on Saturday between Bosnian Croats and Moslems despite the 
agreed ceasefire which became effective at noon on Friday, 
Bosnian Serb military sources said. 
  In the area of Mostar in southern Bosnia-Herzegovina, the 
former allies are engaged in artillery duels while Moslem 
artillery units are firing at Croats in central 
Bosnia-Herzegovina in the region of Novi Travnik, Kiseljak and 
Fojnica. 
  Croats are shelling Moslems in the valley of the Lasva, and 
the shelling is particularly heavy near Gornji Vakuf and 
Bugojno, also in central Bosnia. 
  Regular troops from the Republic of Croatia are also still 
fighting in Bosnia-Herzegovina, despite U.N. Security Council 
decisions that they must withdraw. 
  The Croatian Army launched a strong artillery attack from 
Croatian territory against Serb areas in Posavina, a region in 
northern Bosnia along the border with Croatia. The attack 
directly threatened the Bijeljina-Banja Luka road which links 
eastern and western parts of the Bosnian Serb republic. 
  Bosnian Serb military circles interpreted this attack as 
resulting from the latest Croat-Moslem ceasefire agreement and 
underscored that Bosnian Serb forces did not return fire after 
Croat artillery launched attacks from the left bank of the Sava. 
  Provocative and offensive actions by Moslem units against 
the 
Serb side also continued in former Bosnia-Herzegovina, and were 
even stepped up in some areas, TANJUG learned from Bosnian Serb 
military circles. 
  The heaviest Moslem mortar and artillery attacks took place 
in eastern Bosnia from the regions of Kalesija and Olovo, where 
the Moslem infantry was also active. 
  Meanwhile, Moslem units are regrouping and moving their 
weapons on the Kladanj-Zivinica direction. 
  In northwestern Bosnia, Moslem artillery-infantry attacks on 
Serb territory, which began several days ago, continued from the 
region of Bihac. 

</TEXT>

