<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa To Send Low-Ranking Official to Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702191394 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1800 
GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702191394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A low-ranking official from the president's office 
will be taking part in the work of the parliamentary 
constitutional commission. This was announced by Lech Walesa 
today. 
  [Reporter] My representative, a lower-ranking one, is going 
to return to the commission for formal reasons, the president 
said before leaving Gdansk for Warsaw. It had seemed that the 
constitution should be created at the Sejm, but there is no good 
atmosphere for the president there, Lech Walesa said. He 
announced that in using a different political setup and other 
opportunities he will be preparing his own draft constitution 
and perhaps in the future, under favorable conditions, it might 
be possible to combine both. 
  Asked about reports in some newspapers to the effect that 
Piotr Kolodziejczyk is considering appointing a deputy national 
defense minister from among the present government coalition, 
President Walesa said: This appointment must not be made. 
Anyone who seriously thinks about the state knows that no 
divisions must be created. 
  He offered assistance to the heads of the presidential 
government departments. 
  Lech Walesa would not reply unambiguously to the question of 
whether his press spokesman Andrzej Drzycimski would be either 
resigning or dismissed in the immediate future. Are you feeling 
tired? he asked Drzycimski, and added: I don't think he looks 
all that bad yet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

