<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protests Serb Military Superiority </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502195294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1900 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dear viewers, we have just received a letter sent by 
President Alija Izetbegovic to German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. 
  Dear Mr. Chancellor, I would like to thank you for your 
letter and for the efforts you are investing to help 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and our people. I am particularly grateful 
for the support Germany has lent us in the crucial moments 
before the withdrawal of the Serbian artillery from the hills 
surrounding Sarajevo. The residents of Sarajevo have lived to 
see the end of the two-year nightmare, during which one of every 
four citizens has been killed or wounded. 
  However, the city is still under blockade, and Serbian 
artillery withdrawn from around Sarajevo has obviously been 
redeployed on other battlefields, which has disturbed the 
balance of power on those battlefields. Maglaj and Bihac have 
come under heavy attacks, which could result in thousands of 
fresh victims and further ethnic cleansing. 
  I believe that the final elimination of Serbian artillery is 
a condition for any serious political negotiations. The current 
military imbalance to the advantage of the Serbian side has 
turned the peace negotiations into a diktat. 
  Our hopes for a speedy denouement to the Bosnian crisis are 
linked to resolving our misunderstandings with the Croatians. 
We signed a cease-fire agreement which is to come into effect 
on 25 February. I hope that this time the Croatians will honor 
the agreement and withdraw their forces which, according to the 
UN secretary general's report, consist of at least 5,000 
soldiers of the Army of the Republic of Croatia. The 
involvement on the part of Germany and the United States would 
probably help Bosnia and Croatia find a solution to this 
situation, and to re-establish cooperation in many areas. 
  Yours sincerely, 
  Alija Izetbegovic 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

