<H5>  IV. Miscellaneous or Difficult Terms </H5>
  Bacska = Backa in Serbo-Croatian (partially 
Hungarian-inhabited area of northern Serbia) 
  Baranya = Baranja in Serbo-Croatian (partially 
Hungarian-inhabited area of northern Croatia) 
  Bos = Gabcikovo (Slovak) In keeping with the guidelines on 
bilingual place names, references to the controversial dam 
project on the Danube should be rendered as Gabcikovo in 
headlines and subslugs. In the text, Bos should be retained, 
with [Gabcikovo] in brackets after the first occurrence. When 
the reference is to the original joint Slovak-Hungarian project, 
use Gabcikovo-Nagymaros in headlines and subslugs, retaining 
Bos-Nagymaros in the text. Treat the first occurrence in the 
text as follows: Bos [Gabcikovo]-Nagymaros. 
  Csallokoz = Velky Zitny Ostrov (Slovak) (area between the 
main Danube and its northern branch) 
  Csango = [Partly assimilated Hungarian minority in the 
Moldavian region of Romania] Untranslatable. Avoid in headlines. 
Unless the text provides a definition, put the above in brackets 
after the first occurrence in the text. 
  Delvidek (or delvidek) = ["Southern country"--southern 
Hungary until 1920, now northern Serbia and Croatia]. Do not 
translate. Use the original, putting the above in brackets after 
the first occurrence in the text. Avoid in headlines. 
  Dunantul = [Hungary west of the Danube river] Do not 
translate as Transdanubia, because it may not be clear whether 
the region east or west of the Danube is meant. Use the 
original, putting the above in brackets after the first 
occurrence in the text. Avoid in headlines. Note that the suffix 
"tul" (beyond) indicates west of the Danube but east of the the 
Tisza (see below). 
  Felvidek (or felvidek) = ["Upper country"--northern Hungary 
until 1920, now Slovakia] Do not translate. Use the original, 
putting the above in brackets after the first occurrence in the 
text. Avoid in headlines. 
  Karpatalja = The area of Ukraine on the Western side of the 
Carpathian mountains. In headlines and subslugs, translate as 
"Transcarpathia," which reflects the Ukrainian term for the 
region. However, in the text, translate as Subcarpathia 
(reflecting the Hungarian original). After the first occurrence 
of Subcarpathia in the text, put [Ukraine's Transcarpathian 
region] in brackets. NOTE: When rendering the official 
majority-language form of a place name, use the Ukrainian form 
(rather than the Russian as previously in Soviet times). A 
transliterated list of common place names is appended. 
  Kiralyhagomelleki Reformatus Egyhaz = Kiralyhagomelleki 
[Pasul Craiului (Oradea)] Reformed Church District. NOTE: 
Put Romanian term in brackets after the first occurrence 
only. 
  Magyar = Hungarian 
  Always translate--do not use "Magyars," etc. When the text 
requires distinguishing between citizens of Hungary and 
Hungarians living in other countries, qualify as appropriate 
with a term in brackets: [minority] Hungarians; [ethnic] 
Hungarians; [emigre] Hungarians. 
  Magyarsag (1) = all Hungarians everywhere. 
  Example: A magyarsag erti Istvan kiralynak a. 
  All Hungarians everywhere understand King Stephen's. 
  Magyarsag (2) = being Hungarian; Hungarian identity. 
  Example: Buszke a magyarsagara. 
  He is proud of being Hungarian. 
  Example: Amerikaban is megorizte a magyarsagat. 
  Even in America, he kept his Hungarian identity. 
  nemzet = nation; people 
  nemzetiseg = ethnic minority; ethnic group; nationality 
(citizenship) 
  nemzeti kisebbseg = national minority 
  nemzetalkoto elemek = constituent elements of the nation 
  tarsnemzet = co-nation 
  Szekely = Szekler 
  Szekler is the appropriate English translation, but it is 
obscure. Therefore, avoid in headlines, and put the following in 
brackets after the first occurrence in the text: [sub-group of 
the Hungarian minority in the Transylvanian region of Romania]. 
  Tiszantul = [the region of Hungary east of the Tisza river] 
Do not translate. Use the original, putting the above in 
brackets after the first occurrence in the text. Avoid in 
headlines. 
