<DATE1>  1 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatian, Herceg-Bosna Officials at U.S. Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602190794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1700 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2602190794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Croatian-U.S. talks are being held in 
Washington. The special envoy of President Clinton, Ambassador 
Charles Redman, U.S. Ambassador to Croatia Peter Galbraith, and 
experts of the U.S. Government have had a meeting in the State 
Department with Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic; Kresimir 
Zubak, president of the presidential council of the Croat 
Republic of Herceg-Bosna; and Mile Akmadzic, minister of 
international relations [of Herceg-Bosna]. Also present were 
ambassadors Sarcevic [not further identified] and [Mario] Nobilo. 
  According to initial reports, the United States has 
expressed 
great interest in the implementation of the agreement between 
the Croats and the Muslims both on a federal state of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and on a confederation with Croatia. U.S. 
Vice President Al Gore and Secretary of State Warren Christopher 
are showing great interest. 
  A tripartite meeting has been scheduled for 1830 Central 
European Time at which, in addition to the representatives of 
the Croatian and Muslim sides, U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher and Peter Tarnoff, an official in the State 
Department, will take part. After this half-hour meeting the 
delegations will have talks. These will be led by Minister 
Granic, [Bosnian] Prime Minister Silajdzic, and Ambassador 
Redman. 

</TEXT>

