<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akashi Notes NATO Downed Planes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802225094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2221 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802225094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, February 28 (TANJUG) -- Special envoy of the 
U.N. secretary-general for former Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi said 
on Monday that the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] had not been 
involved in today's action when four planes were downed over 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  It was a NATO action, he said, which was carried out in 
agreement with the United Nations resolution on a no-fly zone 
over Bosnia-Herzegovina, Akashi told Croatian television. 
  Akashi said he had spoken to the commander of NATO's 
southern 
command who had assured him that the regular procedure had been 
respected. 
  Akashi said he had also contacted Bosnian Serb Leader 
Radovan 
Karadzic, telling him that the incident should not be 
dramatised, and that efforts to establish peace should continue. 
  NATO combat planes on Monday downed four planes near Banja 
Luka, a city in the northwest of the Bosnian Serb republic. 
Neither NATO nor the U.N. could determine to which of the 
warring sides in Bosnia the downed planes had belonged. 

</TEXT>

