<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TANJUG on Meaning of NATO `Message' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103133394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1221 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0103133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial by Stevan Cordas] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 1 (TANJUG) - NATO's message, after 
the downing of four aircraft over Bosnia, should have been that 
someone was taught a lesson for violating the U.N. Security 
Council resolution on a no-fly zone, but the world media persist 
in accusing the Bosnian Serbs that the planes belonged to them 
although it is unclear exactly who was taught a lesson. 
  Twenty-four hours after two U.S. F-16s shot down four 
fighters over Bosnia early on Monday [28 February] morning, 
there are still no answers to pertinent questions such as: whose 
were the aircraft, from where did they take off and where did 
the two surviving aircraft land. 
  Despite this, the world media continues accusing the Bosnian 
Serbs by citing unnamed sources and presenting types of the 
downed planes allegedly in the possession of the Bosnian Serb 
Air Force only. 
  Compared to Monday's unison chorus, the world media are on 
Tuesday taking a somewhat more cautious view of the NATO action, 
maybe because NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said he is 
not certain that the downed aircraft belonged to the Bosnian 
Serbs. 
  U.S. Vice-President Al Gore said something along the same 
lines, thus indirectly denying a statement by President Bill 
Clinton who first said that in question are Serb planes, but 
later omitted the word "Serb." 
  NATO, who has monitored the no-fly zone over Bosnia since 
its 
imposition on October 1, 1993, has data showing a total of 
1,400 violations. 
  U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) information clearly shows 
that the Bosnian Serbs are responsible for the least number of 
violations and that no aircraft have taken off from the sole 
Bosnian Serb airport, Banja Luka, since last October. 
  A number of mysteries have yet to be solved. 
  Firstly, how is it possible that NATO does not know from 
where the aircraft took off because it is hard to believe that 
its AWACS planes failed to record this. 
  If this is not the case, it is surprising that NATO has not 
announced what was filmed. 
  Despite this, a number of world agencies "uncovered" that 
the 
downed planes belonged to the Bosnian Serbs. They support these 
claims by unconfirmed reports that these aircraft attacked 
Travnik, although even neutral observers say that the Serbs have 
no reason to bomb this city in central Bosnia. 
  All these unresolved questions create the impression that 
NATO itself does not want to attach special meaning to the 
action over Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7847 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu040_i_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-040 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fate of Bosnian Serb Pilots Described </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103112294 Paris AFP in English 1100 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 1 (AFP) -- A pilot who flew one of 
the four Serb planes shot down by NATO warplanes over Bosnia 
ejected from his aircraft before it was hit and is safe, the 
Belgrade daily POLITIKA said Tuesday [1 March]. 
  His plane crashed in territory controlled by Bosnian Serbs 
between Kljuc and Sanski Most, about 60 kilometers (35 miles) 
west of Banja Luka, from where the Serb planes had flown out, 
according to the paper. It gave no other details on the pilot's 
whereabouts or condition. 
  The pilots of the three other craft are believed to have 
been 
killed when their planes were shot down early Monday during 
missions to attack Moslem positions, one crashing near Bosanski 
Petrovac and the other two near Mrkonjic Grad, both about 60 
kilometers south and southwest of Banja Luka. 
  The paper said the plane that went down near Bosanski 
Petrovac had carried out its bombing mission over Bihac, a 
Moslem enclave in western Bosnia under siege by Bosnian Serbs, 
since it had no bombs on board when it crashed. 
  POLITIKA, which gave no sources for its information, said 
eight Bosnian Serb planes in all had taken off Monday morning 
but only five continued on with their bombing mission. The 
flights were in violation of a ban on military flights over 
Bosnia decreed by the United Nations in April 1993. 
  Bosnian Serb forces have denied that the planes shot down by 
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization were part of their air 
force or that they had taken off from Banja Luka airport, where 
UN observers are posted. 
  The Belgrade-based TANJUG news agency meanwhile said the 
four 
UN observers assigned to monitoring Banja Luka airport were 
staying some 30 kilometers (20 miles) from the site and said 
their vehicles had recently been stolen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

