<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Deny Report of Downed Planes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802134794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1321 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802134794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Kondrashov] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, February 28 (TASS) -- The command of the 
Bosnian Serb Army has categorically refuted a report that air 
force planes of the Serb Republic in Bosnia were brought down 
somewhere over the territory of Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
  "Our air force has only one airfield near Banja Luka, and 
military observers from the U.N. force have long been present 
there. They could have noticed the taking off of planes from 
that airfield without fail," a spokesman for the Serb command 
said in an interview with the TANJUG news agency. 
  The General Staff of the Yugoslav Army also emphatically 
rejected a possibility of four planes, brought down by NATO 
fighters, belonging to the Yugoslav Air Force. 
  Strictly following a resolution of the U.N. Security Council 
banning flights over Bosnia and Herzegovina, our air force 
planes made no flights in that air space. Since the creation of 
the union republic of Yugoslavia, not a single plane belonging 
to it has ever flown outside its air space, said a spokesman for 
the General Staff of the Yugoslav Army. 
  Meanwhile, according to reports of the Moslem Radio of 
Sarajevo, today in the morning military facilities in Moslem 
cities of central Bosnia were bombed by Croatian planes. The 
time of the bombing concides with the action taken by NATO 
fighter planes against planes of the Galeb type. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

