<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Views Serb Denial </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802215994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2802215994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Senad Durkalic] </F>
  [Text] There is no doubt that the planes downed west of 
Banja Luka were Serbian planes, although the Serbs -- true to 
their custom -- denied that this was so. The only unclear point 
is why did the Serbs gamble with NATO's patience? Did they 
expect that they would again get away with their humorless 
jokes, or have they finally started paying the high price of 
their own mistakes? According to as yet unconfirmed information, 
the illogical bombing of Novi Travnik and Bugojno is a fresh 
Serbian ploy designed to pin the blame for the bombing on the 
Croatian aviation, which would result in fresh conflicts between 
the Croatian Defense Council [HVO] and the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army. This would definitely bury the cease-fire signed between 
the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the HVO, and the chetniks -- who 
else -- would profit from this. In any case, the U.S. pilots 
have exhibited their resolve to implement the UN resolutions, 
which will perhaps finally force the Serbs to reconsider their 
megalomaniacal and bestial appetites. An intercepted radio 
message, transmitted a day before the bombing of Novi Travnik, 
and ordered by the Serbian units in Donji Vakuf, reads: 
Tomorrow six of our nightingales will sing the newly composed 
Serbian heroic song about Bugojno. Are we dealing with the 
carelessness of the Serbian ham radio operator, or yet another 
rusty screw in Mladic's propaganda machinery? It does not 
matter. What matters is that four [words indistinct] did not 
work in this case, because how could six sparrows harm two 
falcons? 

</TEXT>

