<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akashi Calls For More Troops in Mostar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802202194 Paris AFP in English 2012 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2802202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mostar, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Feb 28 (AFP) -- Special 
UN envoy to the former Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi on Monday 
called for more troops to be sent to Bosnia to end the "tragedy" 
in the southern city of Mostar. 
  "Sarajevo was a genuine tragedy, but the world should know 
that there are others, perhaps more serious tragedies in a city 
like Mostar," Akashi said as he arrived for his first visit here. 
  Some elements of an agreement that led to a ceasefire in 
Sarajevo had also been tried in an accord reached between 
Bosnian Moslems and Croats besieging the Moslem part of Mostar, 
he added. 
  The accord provides for an interposition of UNPROFOR [United 
Nations Protection Forces] troops between the belligerent 
parties and the withdrawal of heavy weapons to between 20 
kilometers (12 miles) and 10 kilometers (six miles) from the 
city by March 7. 
  Akashi said ceasefire agreements should be signed "in as 
many 
cities as possible. UNPROFOR is prepared to do its best, but 
we're short of troops." 
  In the Moslem-populated eastern sector of Mostar Akashi met 
with members of the city's "war presidency." "President" Smail 
Klaric said Mostar "will have to be an open and non-divided 
city" and be a "part of the Bosnia-Herzegovina territory." 
Croats have laid siege to the Moslem sector for the past nine 
months and have said they want to make the city the capital of a 
self-styled Bosnian Croat republic. Akashi is also to meet with 
Croat officials in the western sector. 
  No fighting was reported in the city Monday after shells 
rained down on the eastern sector Sunday in spite of Friday's 
ceasefire agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

