<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Confirms Resumption of Aid Convoys </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103101694 Paris AFP in English 1006 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 1 (AFP) -- In Geneva, UNHCR 
spokesman Ron Redmond confirmed that the humanitarian airlift to 
Sarajevo would resume Tuesday after a day-long interruption 
following the NATO shooting down of four Serb jets. 
  He said a decision would be made shortly on when to resume 
the UNHCR land convoys crossing Serb territory to different 
points in Bosnia, which were also suspended Monday. 
  "We are receiving the security assessments from UNPROFOR and 
UN observers in Bosnia. The trucks are loaded and ready to go. 
There is a good chance that the convoys will also be going," he 
said. 
  More than 20 airlifts to bring supplies into Sarajevo were 
planned for Tuesday, he said. 
  Though the airlifts and land convoys through Serb territory 
were halted, a dozen other land convoys went ahead as scheduled 
from Metzkovic for different towns in central Bosnia. 
  Of the convoy blocked in Hadzici, Redmond confirmed it had 
been stopped in "Serb-controlled territory by about 100 women 
who were demanding the release of their husbands apparently 
detained by the government forces." 
  "We will try again today to reason with them and get things 
going. If we do, it will be the first time in many months that 
we will be able to use that road," he said. 
  In other developments, a prisoner exchange was made Tuesday 
between 128 Moslems who had been held by Bosnian Croats at Rodoc 
and 61 Croat prisonners detained in Jablanica, the International 
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in Geneva said. 
  The ICRC, which was supervising the exchange, said it had 
also started repatriating 200 displaced Croats, mostly women and 
children, who had been living in difficult circumstances in 
Jablanica. Most had asked to rejoin their families in Mostar, 
in southern Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

