<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Cited on Kovac Accepting Resignations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802164494 Prague CTK in English 1614 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2802164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava Feb 28 (CTK) -- Slovak President Michal 
Kovac will accept the resignations of Deputy Premier Roman Kovac 
and Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik only after the proposal by 
Premier Vladimir Meciar to appoint a new foreign minister is 
approved, presidential spokesman Anton Bodis said today. He 
thus made previous information that Kovac had decided to accept 
the resignations of the two ministers more accurate. 
  Kovac rejected Meciar's proposal to appoint Jozef Prokes, 
current deputy premier and honorary chairman of the Slovak 
National Party (SNS) as new foreign minister today. At the same 
time, Kovac asked Meciar to nominate another person to head the 
Foreign and Privatisation Ministries. 
  Bodis said Meciar had accepted Kovac's request to nominate a 
new candidate to the post of the foreign minister. 
  Meanwhile, government spokesman Ondrej Hanko declined to say 
when the next meeting between Kovac and Meciar would take place 
and who were possible candidates for foreign minister. "That 
would be premature speculation," said Hanko [when] asked whether 
Slovak Ambassador to the Czech Republic Ivan Mjartan was among 
the candidates. 

</TEXT>

