<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Intelligence Chief Primakov Visits </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402082194 Prague CTK in English 1639 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2402082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 23 (CTK) -- The talks on 
cooperation between the Russian and Slovak intelligence services 
are by no means directed against any third country, as they 
primarily concern international crime, Tatyana Samolis, the 
spokeswoman for the director of the Russian Counterintelligence 
Service Yevgeniy Primakov, told journalists today. 
  Primakov, who arrived for a two-day visit to the Slovak 
Republic on Tuesday [22 February], met with deputy chairman of 
Slovak Parliament Augustin Marian Huska and Deputy Premier Jozef 
Prokes. He will also meet President Michal Kovac. 
  Our guest did not raise any objections against Slovakia's 
effort to integrate with European systems, said Huska. 
  "Shall we wait until various parts of the Russian or Chechen 
mafias establish themselves easily in Slovakia?," Huska replied 
to the question whether it was dangerous to establish contacts 
during the current unstable period in the two countries. 
  Both Primakov and Samolis refused to comment on the "Ames 
spying affair." 

</TEXT>

