<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With President Kovac </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402082294 Prague CTK in English 1803 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2402082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 23 (CTK) -- Director of the Russian 
Counterintelligence Service Yevgeniy Primakov, who arrived for a 
two-day visit to the Slovak Republic on Tuesday [22 February], 
told journalists after meeting Slovak President Michal Kovac 
today that no underhanded motives lay behind the timing of his 
visit. 
  Primakov's visit was motivated by the need to create a basis 
for cooperation between the intelligence services of the two 
countries in the fight against international crime, terrorism, 
the drug and arms trades, and the situations in unstable regions 
of Europe, Presidential Spokesman Anton Bodis told journalists. 
  "The cooperation will be not directed against any third 
country," Bodis said, adding that the intelligence services of 
the two countries agreed to exchange representatives in their 
headquarters in order to establish connection. 
  Primakov's Spokeswoman Tatyana Samolis told CTK that the 
talks with the Slovak Intelligence Service would continue 
tonight and tomorrow morning. "The issue was not raised," she 
replied to a question about the activities of Russian agents in 
Slovakia. 

</TEXT>

