<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments on Talks in Latvia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502092494 Warsaw PAP in English 0033 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 24 -- Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski told reporters upon the return of the Polish 
delegation from Latvia on Thursday that economic contacts "along 
with broadly understood supplies of the arms industry" were the 
main topics of talks of the Polish delegation accompanying 
President Lech Walesa. He stressed that Poland has placed 
Latvia and the other Baltic countries among top priorities of 
the Polish eastern policy. 
  He disclosed that he and his Latvian counterpart Georgs 
Andrejevs discussed the possibility of creating a promotion 
centre for the three Baltic countries in Gdansk in the near 
future. According to Olechowski, Polish-Latvian trade exchange 
is insufficient at present, especially that Latvia has already 
regulated its currency issues and there are no problems in 
mutual payments. 
  Rear Admiral Romuald Waga, commander-in-chief of the Polish 
Navy, told reporters that his talks with the defence minister of 
Latvia focused on Polish technical assistance for Latvian Armed 
Forces in organizing communications and trainings. He disclosed 
that the sale of Polish arms to Latvia in exchange for the 
overhaul of marine engines in Latvian shipyards is also being 
considered. Reporters learned that Latvia was interested in the 
purchase of naval guns. 

</TEXT>

