<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Criticizes U.S. Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203161994 Paris AFP in English 1556 GMT 02 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 2 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic criticized the United States Wednesday for its 
role in brokering a Moslem-Croat federation agreement without 
consulting the Serbs, but stopped short of condemning the deal. 
  "We can welcome this agreement only if it is not aimed 
against Serbs. Only if it leads us to peace and not war," he 
said following a meeting here with Vladimir Shumeyko, the 
chairman of the upper house of Russia's parliament, the 
Federation Council. 
  He said the United States was trying to take over the role 
of 
the United Nations in the peace process by brokering the 
agreement Tuesday under which Bosnia's Moslems and Croats would 
form a federation on territory they control in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  He charged that Washington was "biased in favor of the 
Moslems" and voiced concern that the United States was 
"monopolising" the process. "We would like to see America 
unbiased, impartial and then we would accept one power to 
mediate those talks. But I don't think that the United Nations 
should be abandoned and let one power arbitrate," he said. 
  Karadzic, who agreed to Russian requests Tuesday to open 
Tuzla airport in northern Bosnia to humanitarian flights as long 
as this was under Russian supervision, also said he told 
Shumeyko, whose chamber is empowered to authorise the deployment 
of Russian troops abroad, that he was ready to pull back on 
territorial gains made in the 23-month war. 
  "We are ready to give back, to roll back, a big amount of 
territory. (...) We are ready for compromises and we want 
Russia to support us in compromises provided we protect basic 
Serbian national interests," he stated. 
  Karadzic called for "Bosnia's new borders" to be "guaranteed 
by an international agreement at the highest level" and cited a 
proposal by President Boris Yeltsin to hold a five-nation summit 
as an initiative that could lead to such a treaty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

