<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   280 Dutch UN Peacekeepers Leave for Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103162694 Paris AFP in English 1558 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Hague, March 1 (AFP) -- A group of 280 Dutch UN 
peacekeeping soldiers headed to Bosnia Tuesday [1 March] to join 
a Dutch battalion in charge of protecting the Moslem enclaves of 
Srebrenica and Zepa, a Defense Ministry spokesman here said. 
  The soldiers are expected to arrive in the Croat seaside 
city 
of Split Tuesday afternoon. On Wednesday, after recovering 
equipment from a Dutch navy frigate, they are to head to 
Lukavac, where their battalion is based, and then on to 
Srebrenica and Zepa, in eastern Bosnia. 
  The Defense Ministry spokesman said the 280 soldiers will 
bring up to 1,100 the number of Dutch soldiers deployed in 
Bosnia. An additional 150 are expected there by the end of the 
month, he added. Additional Dutch soldiers are deployed in 
ex-Yugoslavia and on air bases in Italy from where they enforce 
the UN no-flight ban over Bosnia. Dutch troops are also 
deployed along the Danube to enforce a trade embargo against 
Serbia. 

</TEXT>

