<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dutch Troops To Relieve Canadians in Srebrenica </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103185794 Paris AFP in English 1803 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 1 (AFP) -- A total of 360 UN Dutch 
troops reached the Moslem enclave of Srebrenica in eastern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to relieve 135 UN Canadian soldiers there, a 
UN spokesman said here Tuesday [1 March]. UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) Lieutenant Colonel Bill Aikman said the Dutch had 
arrived over the past 24 hours. 
  Serb cooperation in allowing a troop rotation in Srebrenica 
was one of three demands of the international community to move 
towards peace in Bosnia. 
  The other two were to withdraw heavy weapons from 
Serb-besieged Sarajevo, which has been done, and to allow the 
re-opening of Tuzla airport in the northeast, which is due to 
take place this month. 
  Serb authorities had blocked the rotation in Srebrenica, 
insisting that the troop level in Srebrenica not increase. 
  But Aikman, a Canadian, said a total of 800-1,000 Dutch 
troops, a full battalion, would deploy in Srebrenica. The Dutch 
have arrived so far with 78 vehicles, mainly armored personnel 
carriers and other troop vehicles. Aikman said the Canadians 
would be leaving in two to three days. 
  Srebrencia is one of six UN-mandated safe areas designed to 
protect besieged Moslem populations. 

</TEXT>

