<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Refuses To Sign Privatization Bill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103150194 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Following a week's break caused by the working 
visit of Vladimir Meciar to the countries of Asia, the Slovak 
Government met in Bratislava today. Deputy Prime Minister Roman 
Kovac and Minister of Foreign Affairs Jozef Moravcik are not 
taking part in its 85th regular session. It is, however, 
expected that the government will adopt a position today on 
personnel questions concerning the posts of minister of foreign 
affairs and minister for administration and privatization of 
national property of the Slovak Republic. The president of the 
Slovak Republic asked Vladimir Meciar for this yesterday. 
  The president refused to appoint Jozef Prokes minister of 
foreign affairs yesterday. The name of Olga Keltosova, minister 
of labor, social affairs, and the family, is being mentioned in 
this connection, as well as that of Ivan Mjartan, Slovak 
ambassador to the Czech Republic. Olga Keltosova, however, has 
allegedly denied her candidature. According to our information 
from government circles, Eva Mitrova, current head of the 
permanent mission of the Slovak Republic at the Council of 
Europe in Strasbourg, is a hot candidate for the post of 
minister of foreign affairs. 
  The candidate for the post of minister for administration 
and 
privatization of national property, according to Vladimir 
Meciar, has been known to the coalition government for several 
months. As he said recently, he has been waiting to appoint him 
only because the position of the government was not stable and 
he considered the appointment of a minister in these 
circumstances illogical. [passage omitted] 
  Ondrej Hanko, head of the government office press 
department, 
has said the following: 
  [Begin Hanko recording] [passage omitted] In the next part 
of 
the session, the prime minister reported on the president's 
letter, which he had received. In this connection, I would like 
to tell you that I have been empowered to deny yesterday's 
statement by the spokesman of the president of the Slovak 
Republic in which he said that the Slovak prime minister agreed 
that the president did not wish to appoint Deputy Prime Minister 
Prokes to the post of minister of foreign affairs. The prime 
minister never uttered these words at yesterday's talks with the 
president. [passage omitted] 
  The prime minister said that he has decided not to sign the 
bill on big privatization that the government passed to the 
president. He stated that he will pass it to the National 
Council for it to be discussed again. [end recording] 
  This was from the session of the government. [passage 
indistinct] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

