<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR Contingent `Inadequately Armed' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103150094 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 28 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Jaroslav Kmenta: "The Czech UNPROFOR Soldiers </F>
Forces Are Inadequately Armed"] 
  [Excerpt] So far, the Czech soldiers of the UN 
peacekeeping forces, operating on the territory of the former 
Yugoslavia, have not been adequately armed. This was 
established by an army inspection headed by Jaromir Novotny, 
director of the Foreign Relations Section at the Defense 
Ministry. 
  The inspection found that, according to the applicable 
tables 
on issue of arms, the soldiers were armed for peace conditions. 
"If something happened, each soldier would certainly have some 
kind of weapon, but we have decided that he will be better 
armed," Novotny said. He emphasized that the army command also 
decided that each UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] battalion will 
have a submachine gun. To date, submachine guns have only been 
used by the soldiers authorized to do so by the appropriate 
standards. 
  Novotny stated that the unit will have guided anti-tank 
missiles at its disposal. 
  The better equipment for the Czech troops will be brought by 
the 117 soldiers who yesterday left the UN peacekeeping forces 
training base in Cesky Krumlov for Karlovac in Croatia. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

