<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oleksy Meets With Media, Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103203394 Prague CT 1 Television Network in Czech 1830 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CT 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Polish Sejm Speaker Jozef Oleksy is ending his visit 
to the Czech Republic today. In his talks he learned that the 
Czech Republic does not wish to change the Visegrad Four into a 
lobby for persuading the European structures to accept these 
countries more swiftly. When meeting the press at the end of 
his talks in Prague, the Polish Sejm speaker said that Poland 
also does not wish for the institutionalization of the Visegrad 
Four and acknowledges that the Czech side emphasizes economic 
cooperation. On the other hand, Poland is convinced that the 
Visegrad Group ought to explain jointly to the West European 
countries its urgent need to join the European structures. 
  In an interview for Czech television, the Polish Sejm 
speaker 
spoke about the current situation in Russia and the possibility 
that Russia would like to play the role of superpower also 
within the Partnership for Peace program. Poland must carefully 
follow developments in Russia where democracy is only in its 
initial stages. Poland must draw its conclusions and bring them 
to the Pan-European discussion. 
  In spite of its firm Euro-Atlantic course, in no way could 
Poland neglect its good economic relations with Russia and 
Ukraine because it sees the [word indistinct] future of Polish 
interests in them also, Mr. Oleksy said. 
  Poland and the Czech Republic are of the opinion that only 
democratic Russia should take part in the structures of the 
Europe of the future and in its future security system. A 
Russia with an imperial policy will not fit into the strategy of 
European security, as it is perceived by Poland and the Czech 
Republic, the Polish Sejm speaker said in Prague today. 

</TEXT>

