<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic Discusses Croat-Muslim Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203133194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1244 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0203133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 2 Mar (TANJUG) -- Federal Foreign Affairs 
Minister Vladislav Jovanovic today said that yesterday's 
Croat-Muslim agreement could be positive if it were to lead to 
an end to the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Talking to reporters in the federal assembly, Jovanovic 
stressed that he was not familiar with the crux of the agreement 
but he nevertheless cautioned that nothing good would come out 
of the agreement if it constituted a block of two sides in 
opposition to the third side, the Serbs, along the lines of 
"take it or leave it." 
  "In that case the agreement would be no contribution to 
peace 
-- on the contrary," Jovanovic said. In his words, the signing 
of the agreement may mean that the Croats and Muslims abandoned 
"what was agreed at an earlier stage in Geneva." 
  "Depending on the essence of this agreement, the Serbian 
side 
will formulate its attitude to it," Jovanovic said. 

</TEXT>

