<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gligorov Views Blockade With German Official </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203173394 Skopje MIC in English 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MIC </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Closed Border--Harmful Consequences"] </F>
  [Text] Macedonia's [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM] President Kiro Gligorov yesterday received 
the State Minister of the Federal Republic of Germany Helmut 
Schafer. The talks were also attended by Macedonia's Foreign 
Minister. 
  On this occasion, they exchanged opinions regarding the 
strengthening of the cooperation between the two countries and 
the current situation in the region. It was jointly assessed 
that the latest Greek measures, namely the closing of the 
border, are illegal, harmful, and that they can cause vast 
consequences to the stability in the region. 
  Gligorov expressed full readiness of Macedonia to resume the 
Macedonian-Greek negotiations within the framework of the UN, 
without previous conditions and pressure. 
  Mr. Schafer yesterday held talks with Foreign Minister Stevo 
Crvenkovski. The two politicians exchanged opinions regarding 
the situation on the Balkans and the mutual bilateral 
cooperation and the possibilities for its strengthening. 
  Minister Crvenkovski briefed the German guest on Macedonia's 
international activities and the efforts for its admission to 
the international institutions. It was jointly concluded that 
there are many possibilities for a development of the bilateral 
relations and economic cooperation. 
  Prime Minister Branko Crvenkovski informed Mr. Schafer of 
the 
latest government measures in relation to the transformation of 
the Macedonian economy, particularly in the implementation of 
the programme for economic stabilization, as well as the 
difficulties Macedonia is facing since the introduction of the 
economic embargo by Greece. 
  Mr. Schafer expressed hope that the newly developed 
situation, following the embargo, will be overcome with an aim 
of normalizing the transport of goods and services on the 
southern Macedonian border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

