<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rose To Meet With Serbs, Muslims on Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103144894 Paris AFP in English 1429 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 1 (AFP) -- UN commander for Bosnia 
British General Michael Rose is to meet Serb and mainly Moslem 
Bosnian military officers Wednesday to discuss ceasefire 
violations, an aide to Rose told AFP. 
  British Lieutenant Colonel Simon Shadbolt, military 
assistant 
to Rose, said Bosnian forces have at some sites advanced their 
front-line positions against besieging Serbs by 10 metres 
(yards). He said Rose would ask the Bosnians to return to their 
original positions. 
  Shadbolt said UNPROFRO has guaranteed the Serbs that the 
Moslems will not advance their lines, or mount an infantry 
attack, while it enforces a NATO exclusion zone that required 
Serb troops to pull their heavy artillery away from Sarajevo. 
The meeting is to be at Sarajevo airport at about noon (1100 
GMT), Shadbolt said. 
  UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) spokesman Canadian 
Lieutenant-Colonel Bill Aikman had said earlier Tuesday that 
while a ceasefire was generally holding in Sarajevo there were 
reports of trench-digging by Bosnian troops in attempts to 
advance their lines. He said violations on the Serb side 
consisted of sniper fire and that there had been small-arms 
shooting on both sides. 

</TEXT>

