<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Boross Comments on Visits to Germany, France </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203220494 Budapest Duna TV in Hungarian 2000 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0203220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Duna TV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Hungarian prime minister has visited two 
European capitals within two weeks. He made a statement to our 
"Newsreel" program after his return. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified correspondent] You have now 
visited Paris and Bonn within a week. Does it mean that these 
two countries are the most important European countries for 
Hungary right now? 
  [Boross] Well, they are two determining powers, members of 
an 
alliance, and are very important for Hungary. I do not think it 
is a coincidence that I visited these two capitals. Germany 
represents a decisive force within the EU [European Union], and 
the fact that it has undertaken to support us in this way means 
that our application [for full EU membership] will be received 
favorably. 
  [Correspondent] [passage omitted] Chancellor Kohl referred 
to 
the intention to put on the EU agenda the ways in which new 
members may be admitted; in other words they want to hold 
negotiations in this respect. How do they see the terms? 
  [Boross] Well, a longer period of preparation and 
negotiation 
faces us, because the Hungarian economy must become suitable for 
admission into the EU. [passage omitted] It must be added that 
there is extraordinarily great interest toward Hungary. As a 
matter of fact, I heard praise about the Hungarian economy's 
ability to absorb capital. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

