<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Forbids Sale of Gas Masks to Croatia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203134394 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 1 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Jaroslav Kmenta: "The United Nations Is </F>
Concerned That Czech Masks Might Be Used by the Croatian Army"] 
  [Text] Prague--The UN Sanctions Committee expressed its 
concerns that the gas masks that the Zubri Rubber Works wanted 
to export to Croatia could ultimately be used by the Army. The 
Croatian Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs stated in the 
purchase request that most of the masks are intended for firemen 
and a smaller number for the civilian population. 
  Dlouhy's Ministry of Industry and Trade originally consulted 
on the sale with the Foreign Ministry, which, in turn, submitted 
the request for assessment to the appropriate UN committee. 
Acting on its recommendation, the License Administration of the 
Ministry of Industry and Trade has not granted the Zubri Rubber 
Works the required export license. 
  A diplomatic official who does not wish to be named for fear 
of difficulties at work told MLADA FRONTA DNES yesterday that, 
although the Czech Republic and Croatia were to be trading 
partners, the actual initiator of the contact was a certain 
Slovak firm that mediated this deal for the Zubri Rubber Works. 
The rubber works would have received almost 45 million korunas 
for the sale of the gas masks to Croatia. 

</TEXT>

