<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic Says Confederation `Very Strong Union' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203200694 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1830 
GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0203200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic in New </F>
York on 2 March after meeting UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali; in English with superimposed Serbo-Croatian 
translation -- recorded] 
  [Text] This is the first step. We will get on with our 
work. We will continue negotiations on a final agreement in 
Vienna and try to finish our work by 15 March. We have signed a 
preliminary agreement on the Croat-Muslim federation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and on the confederation between 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia. It will be a very strong union. 
An agreement on the economy, currency, customs, and other 
issues has been concluded. 
  As for the UN Protected Areas [UNPA's] in Croatia, we are 
expecting a very active mandate on the part of the UN Protection 
Force in the forthcoming period, especially with regard to the 
Croatian borders, disarmament, the establishment of 
communications, and the peaceful reintegration of UNPAs in 
Croatia's legal system. We are ready for talks with local Serbs 
about local autonomy and we are ready for international 
supervision, by the United Nations, the Council of Europe, and 
European Union observers, over human rights, especially the 
rights of the minorities in Croatia. 
  As for the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, we largely 
support NATO's actions so far and we will continue with the 
talks. Croats and Muslims will continue negotiations with the 
Serbs in order that the Serbs can either join the federation or 
that some other agreement can be reached with them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

