<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ready To Continue Talks With Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203203094 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1800 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0203203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Following last night's signing of an agreement 
with Bosnian Prime Minister Silajdzic, Croatian Foreign Minister 
Dr. Mate Granic this afternoon had talks with UN officials -- UN 
Secretary General Butrus-Ghali and Jean Bernard Merimee, French 
ambassador and president of the UN Security Council. Here is 
Jozo Curic with a report from New York: 
  [Curic] Croatia is ready to continue peaceful dialogue with 
the Serbs in UNPA's [UN Protected Areas] areas, Minister Granic 
told UN Secretary General Ghali and UN Security Council 
President Merimee in New York today. He mentioned the principle 
of local autonomy in those UNPA's where Serbs were in the 
majority before the war. Croatia wants the issue of the occupied 
areas to be resolved in line with UN Resolution 871. The UNPA's 
are an integral part of Croatia, Dr. Granic said. 
  According to some UN sources Croatia will ask for a more 
active UNPROFOR mandate, including the use of ultimatum. This 
would mean the implementation of the resolutions that provide 
for the control of borders, for disarmament, the control of 
roads, measures to restore confidence, and the economic recovery 
of these areas. Minister Granic informed his hosts about the 
Croat-Muslim outline agreement on a federation and the 
preliminary agreement on a loose confederation of Croatia and 
the Bosnia-Herzegovina federation. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

