<H3> <TI>   NATO Offers Partnership for Peace Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203191794 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1800 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0203191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Following Slovenia's diplomatic actions over the 
past few weeks, our country was officially offered membership in 
the Partnership for Peace program in Brussels. Slovenia will 
join this program as the first country that is not a member of 
the NATO Cooperation Council. Edo Zitnik has the details: 
  [Begin Zitnik recording] The NATO pact has now also 
officially offered cooperation in the Partnership for Peace to 
Slovenia as the 11th East European country. [passage omitted] 
  Because each country signs the Partnership for Peace with 
NATO individually, its concrete contents will depend greatly on 
the Slovene offers for cooperation. We must keep in mind that 
Slovenia is not among the first in the Partnership and that 
other countries, because of their greater strategic importance, 
have already taken the best that NATO has offered. [passage 
omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

