<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Assesses Offer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203205394 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1800 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0203205394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Our Foreign Ministry accompanied a decision about 
Slovenia's participation in the Partnership for Peace with a 
special statement: 
  In the introduction, the statement mentions a letter that 
Foreign Minister Lojze Peterle sent to the foreign ministers of 
its member-states prior to the 5 February NATO summit, a visit 
by the U.S. President's special envoy Madeleine Albright to 
Slovenia, and a letter that our Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek 
sent to [NATO] prime ministers together with a formal 
application for the participation of our country in the 
Partnership for Peace. 
  The Foreign Ministry emphasizes that, by being admitted into 
the Partnership for Peace, Slovenia has accomplished an 
important step in drawing closer to the Western European 
integrations, also in the realm of security. Today's decision 
of the NATO Council in Brussels represents a materialization of 
the efforts of our state organs in the implementation of the 
Resolution on Guidelines of the National Security Concept, which 
was passed by the Slovene Parliament in February. 
  We are supposed to sign a cooperation document in the coming 
days. After the talks with the NATO political and military 
experts, our country will get another opportunity to appoint its 
military and political representatives to NATO Headquarters in 
Brussels, is written in a statement by the Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

