<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protest Sent to Croatia on Border Construction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203182494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1703 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0203182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, Mar 2 (TANJUG) -- Slovenia's Foreign 
Ministry on Wednesday sent a protest note to Croatia because of 
the resumption of construction works on Croatia's border 
crossing in the vicinity of the Slovenian resort of Portoroz. 
  Slovenian authorities maintain that Croatia's customs 
authorities are constructing facilities on Slovenia's territory 
and demand that the works be discontinued until the final 
demarcation in area. 
  The construction works were discontinued in May last year 
after strong protests by Slovenia. Croatia, however, decided to 
resume construction works which is expected to cause further 
straining of Slovenian-Croatian relations which have already 
deteriorated as a result of disputes over land and maritime 
borders and electric power deliveries from the Krsko nuclear 
power plant. 
  Inhabitants of the Kantrida settlement in the Croatian port 
of Rijeka in [word indistinct] particular way expressed 
dissatisfaction with Slovenia's policy towards Croatia and the 
deteriorating relations between Ljubljana and Zagreb. 
  On a number of ocassions they threw stones at trains on the 
Rijeka-Ljubljana line, the Rijeka police said. 
  In the exchange of diplomatic letter between Croatia and 
Slovenia concerning the incident, the Croatian side promised, as 
it was underscored, that it will "prevent vandal actions of its 
citizens." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

